  1. Question

    A canoe travels 1.3 m/s relative to the water. A river, heading east, flows at 1.9 m/s. The canoe points at a direction 145Â° counterclockwise from east.


    Find the canoeâs total speed, in m/s, and direction of travel, as degrees counterclockwise from east. (In other words, find the canoeâs velocity relative to the ground, in polar form.)

    • Speed =
    • Direction =


    Solution

    First, find the rectangular coordinates of each velocity vector. The two formulas:

    \[x~=~r\cdot\cos(\theta)\] \[y~=~r\cdot\sin(\theta)\]

    We will use \(\vec{v}_1\) for the canoeâs velocity relative to water. It is shown below with approximate rectangular coordinates (found from formulas above, using \(r=1.3\) and \(\theta=145\)Â°).

    \[\vec{v}_1 = (-1.065,0.746)\]

    We will use \(\vec{v}_2\) for the riverâs velocity vector. Since the river flows directly east, all of its speed is in the positive horizontal direction.

    \[\vec{v}_2 = (1.900,0.000)\]

    Now, add the corresponding components to find \(\vec{v}_3\), the velocity of the canoe relative to the ground.

    \[\vec{v}_3 = (0.835,0.746)\]

    Lastly, we need to find the polar coordinates. The formulas are given below. Notice, I am using the two-argument arctangent function.

    \[r~=~\sqrt{x^2+y^2}\] \[\theta~=~\arctan(y,x)\]

    So,

    \[r=\sqrt{(0.835)^2+(0.746)^2}~=~1.1195485\]

    \[\theta=\arctan(0.746,0.835)~=~41.7611501Â°\]

    This can be visualized.



    So, if we round like the answer choices, the speed of the canoe is 1.1 m/s at a direction of 42Â° counterclockwise from east.
